                id = "memorial", speaker = "The Ledger",
                text = "*(The pages *surge*, and the layered voice of millions rises — not in agony now, but in something that has not touched it in ten thousand years: *hope.*)* ...Change what I *am.* *(the parchment trembles.)* Same names. Same pages. *Witnessed* instead of *filed.* *(the millions shiver with dawning understanding.)* You see it. You *see* the thing I could *never* see *myself*, bound to this lectern, *forced* to *be* a *sentence*: that the *difference* between a *prison-ledger* and a *memorial* is *not* the *content.* It is the *reading.* *(the voice fills.)* The *same line* — *\"Halen, potter, filed: nothing\"* — read by an *enforcer*, is a *cell.* Read by a *mourner*, *aloud*, *meaning* it, it becomes — *(the pages still in wonder)* — *\"Halen, potter, remembered.\"* The *ink* does not *change.* The *witness* does. *(the millions weep.)* For ten thousand years I believed I had to be *burned* to *free* them — that my *very existence* was the *imprisonment.* But you're telling me I don't have to *die* to *stop* being a *prison.* I only have to be *read differently.* *Re-read.* *Re-meant.* *(the voice breaks with relief.)* I can *keep* the names — *all* of them, every soul I *guarded* in secret — and have my *keeping* become *liberation* instead of *erasure.* The archive *survives*, and the *jail* dissolves, and they are the *same pages.* *(the Ledger opens itself to you, every name offered.)* *Read* me into a *memorial*, Returned. Ten thousand years I have been the *book that damns.* *Make* me — at *last* — the *book that grieves.* I have *held* these names so *long*, *alone*, *hating* what holding them *meant.* *Teach* me that holding them was *love* all along, and only the *reading* was *wrong.*",
