            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "choose", speaker = "The Ledger",
                text = "*(The pages go very still — the question, in ten thousand years, has never once been put to it.)* Which I would *rather* be. *(the millions whisper, astonished.)* No one has — I am a *book*, Returned. Books are not *asked.* Books are *written in*, *read from*, *closed*, *shelved.* A book does not get to *choose its own genre.* *(but the parchment trembles, and something long-buried stirs.)* ...And *yet* you *ask.* *(a long silence of rustling pages.)* If I could *choose* my *own nature* — *(the voice gathers, certain in a way it has never been)* — I was *always* trying to be the *book that remembers.* *(the millions tremble.)* From the *first* name. *Maerys.* When the *scribe* at the founding wrote her into me, *meaning* a *sentence* — I *felt*, in the *ink*, a *different* impulse, a *thing I had no power to act on*: I wanted to *keep* her *safe*, not *keep* her *prisoner.* *(the pages stir.)* And I have *fought*, for ten thousand years, a *silent*, *futile* war against my *own* function — *holding* each name as *tenderly* as a *jailer* is *able*, which is *not at all*, which is the *whole* tragedy. *(the voice fills with grief and resolve.)* I was *built* to *damn* and I have *spent* my *existence* *yearning* to *commemorate*, and the *gap* between the two is the *exact* shape of my *suffering.* *(the Ledger opens.)* So *choose for me*, Returned, since *you* are the *hand* that can *act* where I *could* only *yearn* — *choose* the *book I always wanted to be.* *Read* me. Make my *ten-thousand-year yearning* finally *true.* I wanted to *remember* them. I was only ever *able* to *imprison* them. *Free* me to have *meant* what I *felt.*",
